'''Wakenosu Shrine''' (わけのすじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in Shimonishi, {{ill|lt=Okinoshima Town|Q1205039|WD=Q1205039|1=Okinoshima, Shimane}}, {{ill|lt=Oki District|Q735735|WD=Q735735|1=Oki District, Shimane}}, {{ill|lt=Shimane Prefecture|Q132751|WD=Q132751|1=Shimane Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}} (minor shrine), and its former shrine rank was village shrine. Its common name is '''Matsuo Shrine'''.

=== Overview ===
The year of enshrinement is unknown, but it is identified as the shrine corresponding to “Wakenosu-no-Mikoto Shrine” listed in the *{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}*{{sfn|Takahashi et al., eds.|1996|p=495}}. In the *{{ill|lt=Kokunai Jinmyōchō|Q11420490|WD=Q11420490|lt=Oshu Jinmyōchō|1=Izumi Province Divine Name Register}}*, it is recorded as the collective shrine of Shimonishi under the name “Junior First Rank Wakenosu Ōmyōjin”{{sfn|Handa|1983|p=979}}{{efn|This “Junior First Rank” is thought to refer to a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Sōgen Senji|1=UNKNOWN}} decree{{sfn|Handa|1983|p=980}}.}}. In {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 5 (1872), it was ranked as a village shrine{{sfn|Handa|1983|p=980}}.

Commonly called “Matsuo Shrine,” it is known as a deity of {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=sake brewing|1=UNKNOWN}} {{sfn|Takahashi et al., eds.|1996|p=495}}{{efn|Because the mountain stream flowing beside the shrine precincts provided high-quality water suitable for brewing sake, the name was written as “Wakenosake.” It is also said that in the medieval period, {{ill|lt=Matsuo Taisha|Q710302|WD=Q710302|lt=Matsuo Myōjin|1=Matsunoo Taisha}} was invited from {{ill|lt=Yamashiro Province|Q749276|WD=Q749276|1=Yamashiro Province}}{{sfn|Handa|1983|p=979}}. There is also a theory that it came to be regarded as a deity of sake brewing only after the name began to be written as “Wakenosake”{{sfn|Rikabi-no-ya|1987c|p=293}}.}}. The shrine crest is a “gourd within a circle”{{sfn|Takahashi et al., eds.|1996|p=494}}.

=== Enshrined Deity ===
'''Wakenosu-no-Mikoto''' (わけのすのみこと)

This deity is thought to be related to Mizuwakasu-no-Mikoto of {{ill|lt=Mizuwakasu Shrine|Q11549109|WD=Q11549109|1=Mizuwakasu Shrine}} and Tamawakasu-no-Mikoto of {{ill|lt=Tamawakasu-no-Mikoto Shrine|Q11572773|WD=Q11572773|1=Tamawakasu-no-Mikoto Shrine}}. While the divine nature is unclear, there are two major views: one that considers the deity a personal god, and another that sees it as a nature god{{sfn|Rikabi-no-ya|1987a|p=184}}.

* Personal Deity Theory  
: This view is typified by an essay included in *Shimane Prefectural History* by Shimizu Shinzaburō{{sfn|Shimizu|1923}}{{sfn|Rikabi-no-ya|1987a|p=184}}{{sfn|Rikabi-no-ya|1987b|p=256}}. Shimizu regarded “mizu (water) = mizu (auspicious)” and “tama (jewel)” as honorific expressions, and assumed a blood relationship between the two Wakasu deities{{sfn|Shimizu|1923|p=227}}. He then argued: “1. During the reign of {{ill|lt=Emperor Keikō|Q329723|WD=Q329723|lt=Keikō|1=Emperor Keikō}}, imperial relatives were distributed across various provinces and so-called ‘branch’ administrations were established”{{sfn|Shimizu|1923|pp=228–229}}; “2. The fifth imperial prince of Keikō, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ōsu-wake no Ōji|1=UNKNOWN}}, seems to have been assigned to Oki as a ‘branch’ and governed there”{{sfn|Shimizu|1923|pp=229–230}}; “3. Wakenosu-no-Mikoto Shrine likely enshrines Ōsu-wake-no-Mikoto”{{sfn|Shimizu|1923|pp=230–232}}. From this, he inferred that Mizuwakasu-no-Mikoto and Tamawakasu-no-Mikoto, whose ancestral shrine was Wakenosu-no-Mikoto Shrine, divided and governed {{ill|lt=Dōgo Island|Q3623017|WD=Q3623017|1=Dōgojima}}{{sfn|Shimizu|1923|p=231}}. In other words, this theory identifies the enshrined deity '''Wakenosu-no-Mikoto with Prince Ōsu-wake'''.

* Nature Deity Theory  
: This view is represented by Shiga Tsuyoshi’s *Studies on Shikinaisha*{{sfn|Shiga|1981}}{{sfn|Rikabi-no-ya|1987a|p=184}}. Shiga considered Wakenosu-no-Mikoto to be a shortened form of “Wakenowakasu-no-Mikoto,” with the “waka” omitted, and regarded the shrine as corresponding to a subsidiary shrine of Tamawakasu-no-Mikoto Shrine{{sfn|Shiga|1981|p=558}}. As for the divine nature, he inferred it to be '''a deity who causes the water of a pond beside the shrine to spring forth'''{{sfn|Shiga|1981|p=558}}. He further interpreted Tamawakasu-no-Mikoto as meaning “causing jeweled water to spring forth,” based on the exceptionally pure groundwater of Shimonishi Village where Tamawakasu-no-Mikoto Shrine is located{{sfn|Shiga|1981|p=557}}; and Mizuwakasu-no-Mikoto as a deity who causes pure water to spring forth (“Mizu-wakasu-no-Mikoto”), focusing on the Yamada River flowing through Yamada, the former shrine site of Mizuwakasu Shrine, and the place name {{ill|lt=Ochi District|Q11597172|WD=Q11597172|lt=Ochi|1=Ochi district}} meaning “rejuvenating water”{{sfn|Shiga|1981|p=561}}. While he considered Tamawakasu-no-Mikoto Shrine and Mizuwakasu Shrine to be symmetrical, he did not posit a direct relationship among the enshrined deities of these three shrines{{sfn|Shiga|pp=557, 560}}.

=== Facilities ===
;Main Hall  
: A modified {{ill|lt=Kasuga-zukuri|Q3193781|WD=Q3193781|1=Kasuga-zukuri}}{{efn|Some sources describe it as {{ill|lt=Oki-zukuri|Q11659055|WD=Q11659055|1=Oki-zukuri}}{{sfn|Handa|1983|p=980}}.}}, measuring 1 ken in width and 1.3 ken in depth{{sfn|Takahashi et al., eds.|1996|p=495}}. The erection of the main hall’s pillars is thought to date to {{ill|lt=Kansei|Q1195131|WD=Q1195131|1=Kansei}} 2 (1790){{sfn|Handa|1983|p=980}}.
;Connecting Hall  
: {{ill|lt=Kirizuma-zukuri|Q13308575|WD=Q13308575|1=Kirizuma-style}}{{sfn|Handa|1983|p=980}}, measuring 1.3 ken in width and 2.3 ken in depth{{sfn|Takahashi et al., eds.|1996|p=495}}.
;Worship Hall  
: {{ill|lt=Irimoya-zukuri|Q855025|WD=Q855025|1=East Asian hip-and-gable roof}}{{sfn|Handa|1983|p=980}}, measuring 2.1 ken in width and 2.1 ken in depth{{sfn|Takahashi et al., eds.|1996|p=495}}.
;Pilgrims’ Lodging{{sfn|Takahashi et al., eds.|1996|p=495}}  
: In Oki, there was a custom called “okomori,” in which people would pray at their tutelary shrine for recovery from illness, safe childbirth, abundant catches, or school admission, and then, as thanks for fulfillment, spend a night secluded in a hut called “komosha” or “komoriya” located within the shrine precincts{{sfn|Ōtsu|1973|p=310}}.
;Torii  
: Myōjin-style torii{{sfn|Handa|1983|p=980}}.

